Request Description
### Add New User This endpoint allows you to add a new user to the system. #### Request Body - `name` (string, required): The name of the user. - `gender` (string, required): The gender of the user. - `email` (string, required): The email address of the user. - `status` (string, required): The status of the user. #### Response Upon successful creation, the endpoint returns the details of the newly created user including: - `id` (integer): The unique identifier of the user. - `name` (string): The name of the user. - `email` (string): The email address of the user. - `gender` (string): The gender of the user. - `status` (string): The status of the user. Example Response: ``` json { "id": 0, "name": "", "email": "", "gender": "", "status": "" } ```

### Get Users This endpoint sends an HTTP GET request to retrieve a list of users from the server. **Request Body** This request does not require a request body. **Response** The response will include an array of user objects, where each object contains the following fields: - `id` (number): The unique identifier for the user. - `name` (string): The name of the user. - `email` (string): The email address of the user. - `gender` (string): The gender of the user. - `status` (string): The status of the user. Example response: ``` json [ { "id": 0, "name": "", "email": "", "gender": "", "status": "" } ] ```

### Get Users This endpoint sends an HTTP GET request to retrieve a list of users from the server. **Request Body** This request does not require a request body. **Response** The response will include an array of user objects, where each object contains the following fields: - `id` (number): The unique identifier for the user. - `name` (string): The name of the user. - `email` (string): The email address of the user. - `gender` (string): The gender of the user. - `status` (string): The status of the user.
